## **✅ Step 3: Create a Mapper (`FinancialInstitutionMapper.java`)**
```java
package jp.co.mycompany.servicing.mapper;

import jp.co.mycompany.servicing.dto.FinancialInstitutionDTO;
import jp.co.mycompany.servicing.model.FinancialInstitution;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

@Component
public class FinancialInstitutionMapper {

    public FinancialInstitutionDTO toDTO(FinancialInstitution entity) {
        FinancialInstitutionDTO dto = new FinancialInstitutionDTO();
        dto.setFinancialInstitutionCode(entity.getFinancialInstitutionCode());
        dto.setFinancialInstitutionBranchCode(entity.getFinancialInstitutionBranchCode());
        dto.setOrder(entity.getOrder());
        dto.setNameKana(entity.getNameKana());
        dto.setName(entity.getName());
        dto.setBranchNameKana(entity.getBranchNameKana());
        dto.setBranchName(entity.getBranchName());
        dto.setPostalCode(entity.getPostalCode());
        dto.setAddress(entity.getAddress());
        dto.setClearingHouseNumber(entity.getClearingHouseNumber());
        dto.setDateOfApplication(entity.getDateOfApplication());
        dto.setEndDateOfApplication(entity.getEndDateOfApplication());
        dto.setPhoneNumbers(entity.getPhoneNumbers());
        return dto;
    }

    public List<FinancialInstitutionDTO> toDTOList(List<FinancialInstitution> entities) {
        return entities.stream().map(this::toDTO).collect(Collectors.toList());
    }
}
```
✔ **Converts Entity to DTO, removing unnecessary fields.**  
✔ **Ensures clear separation between database and API response.**  

